#compdef fyin
# ============================================================================
# fyin - Open source CLI alternative to Perplexity AI (Rust, AGPL-3.0)
#
# Author : Suresh Yarra (shadowfax92)
# Upstream: https://github.com/shadowfax92/Fyin
#
# fyin queries an OpenAI-compatible chat model with grounded context fetched
# from Bing Web Search results that have been live-scraped from each result
# URL. The HTML extraction lane is built on the `scraper` crate by the
# rust-scraper org (https://github.com/rust-scraper/scraper), which exposes
# the `Html::parse_document` entry point and the `Selector::parse` builder
# over the `html5ever` tokenizer + `selectors` crate from Servo. See
# `src/scraper.rs` upstream:
#
#     use scraper::{Html, Selector};
#     let document = Html::parse_document(&body);
#     let selector_p = Selector::parse(
#         "body p, body h1, body h2, body h3, article p, div p, span p"
#     ).unwrap();
#     for element in document.select(&selector_p) {
#         if let Some(text) = element.text().next() {
#             main_text.push_str(&clean_text(text));
#         }
#     }
#
# This is the canonical use of the crate: build a CSS selector once, walk a
# parsed document, project text content out of matching nodes. Every HTML
# scraper in the Rust ecosystem that wants jQuery-style ergonomics over
# Servo's HTML stack lands here; the crate is now at 2300+ stars on
# github.com/rust-scraper/scraper and is the de-facto choice for
# selector-driven scraping in Rust.
#
# Required runtime env (read via dotenv from .env or shell):
#   OPENAI_API_KEY        - OpenAI-compatible API key
#   BING_SUBSCRIPTION_KEY - Bing Web Search API key (Azure cognitive services)
#   EMBEDDING_MODEL_NAME  - e.g. text-embedding-ada-002
#   CHAT_MODEL_NAME       - e.g. gpt-4 / gpt-4-turbo
#
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# AXIS 195 :: HTML SCRAPING WITH CSS SELECTORS
# Round 1283 :: Rust slot 1 of 4 :: OPENS Axis 195
#
# Cross-language canonical library family for this axis:
#   Rust    : scraper      (rust-scraper/scraper)  - html5ever + selectors
#   Go      : goquery      (PuerkitoBio/goquery)   - net/html + cascadia
#   TS/Node : cheerio      (cheeriojs/cheerio)     - parse5 + css-select
#
# All three libraries expose the same conceptual surface - "parse HTML once,
# select with CSS, project text/attrs" - but trace back to different parser
# stacks. scraper rides Servo's `html5ever` + `selectors`; goquery wraps
# the Go stdlib `golang.org/x/net/html` tokenizer plus `andybalholm/cascadia`
# for selector matching; cheerio wraps inikulin's `parse5` HTML5 parser plus
# fb55's `css-select` selector engine. The three stacks were written
# independently and converged on the same jQuery-ish API surface that web
# developers already know from selecting CSS in browsers.
#
# fyin is the Rust slot - a real-world Perplexity-clone CLI that proves
# `scraper` survives noisy production HTML from arbitrary Bing-returned
# pages. AGPL-3.0 licensed; 231 stars; archived as a working alpha by the
# author. The dependency is declared at top-level Cargo.toml:
#
#     scraper = "0.19.0"
#
# verified verbatim by GitHub API call against shadowfax92/Fyin@HEAD.
# ============================================================================

_fyin() {
    local context state state_descr line
    typeset -A opt_args

    _arguments -s -S \
        '(-q --query)'{-q,--query}'[search query string (required)]:query string:' \
        '(-s --search)'{-s,--search}'[number of search results to scrape and feed to the LLM]:result count (default 10):' \
        '(- *)'{-h,--help}'[print help information]' \
        '(- *)'{-V,--version}'[print version information]'
}

_fyin "$@"
